    "created_at": "2016-04-12T06:40:42Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-04-12T06:40:42Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "I agree for 2 reasons:\n1. RFC6979-compliant k values for digital signatures are more provably-unguessable than values retrieved from a CSPRNG. Problems with the CSPRNG call (like a library issue) could cause it to return 0 or 1 all the time, or return sequences of values across multiple calls that can be guessed (if it's always seeded with the same value). Calculating the value deterministically based on hashes of the data itself can be proven to be unguessable by ensuring the returned value conforms to the expected hash of the contents\n2. It will allow all systems built on go-ethereum to reach the L3 requirement for [1.04 Key Usage](https://cryptoconsortium.github.io/CCSS/Details/#1.04) in the [CryptoCurrency Security Standard](https://cryptoconsortium.github.io/CCSS/) \n",
